@ledaiduongvnth 

Just wanted to confirm that this isn't a memory leak with OpenVINO. Memory leak is when there is improper usage of dynamic memory that is been getting allocated in the heap or the excess and unused memory is not getting freed before the application is getting terminated.

I will now try to explain, what is happening, with this specific sample when you are trying to run with OpenVINO Execution Provider with the help of a small code snippet as below. Also note that this issue was only seen with dynamic models with OpenVINO.

**while  (true){
        // Create random number between 640 and 2500
        int range = 2500 - 640 + 1;
        int num = rand() % range + 640;
        std::vector<int64_t> inputDims {1, 3, num, num};
}**

so, what is happening is, for every iteration, you are trying to pass some random input shape to this dynamic model.
with every iteration, it's a different input dimension and every time a new blob is created w.r.t hardware and gets stored as cache and today OpenVINO-EP has no limit for the number of cache blobs that could be available. There can be any number of cache blobs be created.

so if you observe, as the inference is happening, with time, the cpu memory usage keeps going up as with every iteration a cache blob is getting added up w.r.t new input_shape for the model per iteration.

And this is the reason, why the CPU memory section is shooting up with time.

In future, we would like to limit the number of cache blobs that we would like to have at one point of time. But currently, we don't have this feature because practically such use case doesn't exist.

@ledaiduongvnth currently, we don't have this feature to limit the number of cache blobs. so, I am not sure if there's any workaround for this.

so for your dynamic model, you can try pre-processing the input shape of the data to one fixed size and try to compare the accuracy tradeoff between it and when you try to run with different input shape every time.

If you still think, you aren't happy with the accuracy drop, I would suggest you to use default cpu provider for your task or use case.
